00:22:16.180 --> 00:22:20.820
with heat up above where we're discharging heat up in the top of the gym floor,

00:22:21.060 --> 00:22:23.460
but that heat never gets down to the floor level.

00:22:23.955 --> 00:22:26.035
And our thermostats are at the floor level.

00:22:26.195 --> 00:22:28.595
So what happens is when it gets really, really cold

00:22:28.835 --> 00:22:33.555
is we've got heaters that just run and run and run trying to push that heat down to those thermostats.

00:22:33.955 --> 00:22:35.075
The problem is

00:22:35.395 --> 00:22:41.700
you have to use excessive amount of fuel, and the the ceiling temperature can get a 100 to 120 degrees

00:22:41.860 --> 00:22:45.700
to get that gradient down to 70 degrees where those thermostats are gonna shut off.

00:22:46.100 --> 00:22:58.875
So what these ceiling fans in the past were always thought to push air down, but if as you see in the video, they create a lot of turbulence on the outside, and they never really have a column, and they never really force the air down to the ground level.

00:22:59.275 --> 00:23:05.035
So this this got popular in Europe. It's it's called de stratification. So it basically what these fans do is they take

00:23:05.410 --> 00:23:17.490
it's basically a tube with a fan in it, and it basically forces a column of air down to the floor level. And it mixes that hot hundred hundred to 120 degree air in with that floor air, which

00:23:18.095 --> 00:23:19.615
satisfies the thermostats

00:23:19.935 --> 00:23:24.415
and allows you the heating cycles to be less and to basically conserve

